Creating an automatic table of contents in a LaTeX document is a fundamental aspect of organizing and navigating through the various sections and subsections of your document. LaTeX provides a straightforward way to achieve this through its built-in functionalities. Below is a step-by-step example showcasing how to generate a table of contents, including the necessary commands:

### Step 1: Preambles and Document Class

First, you start with the preambles where you include necessary packages and define document-wide settings. Then, you begin the document with the appropriate document class. For a typical article or report, you might use the `article` or `report` class.

```latex
\documentclass{article} % or use 'report' for a more extensive document

\usepackage{hyperref} % Optional, for clickable links in the TOC and cross-references

\begin{document}
```

### Step 2: Using Sections and Subsections

To make a table of contents meaningful, you need to structure your document using sectioning commands (`\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, etc.). These commands help LaTeX understand the document structure and generate the table of contents accordingly.

```latex
\title{Example Document}
\author{Author Name}
\date{Date}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\subsection{Background}
This subsection provides background information.

\section{Main Body}
\subsection{First Main Section}
Content of the first main section goes here.

\subsubsection{Sub-subsection}
Further details under the first main section.

\section{Conclusion}
This section concludes the document.
```

### Step 3: Generating the Table of Contents

To automatically generate the table of contents, you use the `\tableofcontents` command after the `\begin{document}` line but before any sectioning commands (though it's generally good practice to place it right after the document title and author information). LaTeX will compile the information from your sectioning commands and create a table of contents that reflects the structure of your document.

```latex
\tableofcontents % This command generates the table of contents
```

### Complete Example

Combining all the steps, your complete LaTeX document for generating an automatic table of contents would look like this:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{hyperref} % Optional for clickable TOC and cross-references

\begin{document}

\title{Example Document}
\author{Author Name}
\date{Date}

\maketitle

\tableofcontents % Generates the table of contents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\subsection{Background}
This subsection provides background information.

\section{Main Body}
\subsection{First Main Section}
Content of the first main section goes here.

\subsubsection{Sub-subsection}
Further details under the first main section.

\section{Conclusion}
This section concludes the document.

\end{document}
```

### Note:
- Compiling a LaTeX document with a table of contents usually requires at least two passes. In the first pass, LaTeX gathers all the sectioning information. In the second pass, it updates the page numbers and other details in the table of contents. Most LaTeX editors handle this process automatically.
- The `hyperref` package is optional but highly recommended if you want your table of contents (and any cross-references in your document) to have clickable links.

This example demonstrates the fundamental method for generating a table of contents in a LaTeX document, ensuring that your document is well-organized and easily navigable.

To draw a chessboard state represented by a Forsyth-Edwards Notation (FEN) in LaTeX, you can utilize the `chessfigures` package along with the `chessboard` package. The `chessfigures` package provides the necessary figures for the chess pieces, while the `chessboard` package allows you to construct a chessboard based on a FEN description.

Below is a step-by-step guide and a LaTeX code snippet that demonstrates how to include and use these packages to draw a chessboard based on a given FEN. For this example, let's consider a simple FEN string: `"rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"` which represents the starting position of a standard chess game.

### Step 1: Include Required Packages

First, include the necessary packages in the preamble of your LaTeX document. You'll need `chessboard` and `chessfigures`.

```latex
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{chessfigures}
```

### Step 2: Load Figures

Before drawing the board, load the chess figures using the `loadfigure` command. This step is crucial for displaying the actual pieces on the board.

```latex
\chessfigureload{png} % Specify the format of the figures (e.g., png, pdf)
```

### Step 3: Draw the Chessboard

With the packages included and the figures loaded, you can now draw the chessboard based on the FEN notation. Use the `ChessBoard` command followed by your FEN string within the document body.

```latex
\begin{center}
    \newchessgame
    \ChessBoard[boardstyle={utf8style}, size=200]{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}
\end{center}
```

- `boardstyle={utf8style}` is used for styling the board. You can adjust this according to your preference.
- `size=200` adjusts the size of the chessboard. Modify this value to fit your document layout.
- The `ChessBoard` command takes the FEN string as an argument.

### Complete LaTeX Code

Combining all the steps, here is a complete LaTeX document that includes a chessboard drawn from a FEN notation:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{chessfigures}

\begin{document}

\title{Chessboard from FEN}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}
\maketitle

\begin{center}
    \newchessgame
    \chessfigureload{png} % Adjust based on the format of your figures
    \ChessBoard[boardstyle={utf8style}, size=200]{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

Compile this LaTeX code using a LaTeX compiler that supports these packages (like pdflatex with the required package installations). This will generate a PDF document displaying the chessboard in its initial state as specified by the FEN notation.

Remember, the actual visual appearance (e.g., piece styles and board texture) can be customized by adjusting the options provided by the `chessboard` and `chessfigures` packages. Refer to the documentation of these packages for more customization options.

